<font color="#FF0000">THE POST WAR GENERATION</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 26  1:01:23 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I am nineteen years old, so I guess that makes me a part of the post-war generation, as well. The Vietnam War hung over my childhood, a big mystery as to the meaning of it all.  Only this year in college, I finally linked it to the fear of Communism, another of those mysterious terms that everyone hated though I didn't know why. I knew there was much shame associated with the war. Shame that we were involved, shame that American lives were lost, shame that innocent Vietnamese children and mothers were killed.  And, I have heard that these veterans were not so celebrated as past war veterans. I guess because we not clear winners, and Americans like winners.  We play with wars like they are football games sometimes, it seems.  So, I am still trying to understand Vietnam. When I was younger, I thought mistakenly that the Persian Gulf could be our Vietnam, which it wasn't.  I can only imagine the loss of people my age, probably many from my high school who haven't gone on to college.  I visited the Wall in D.C., but I still cannot comprehend the total effect of growing up in those time. Yet it seems to be a legacy my generation missed yet every other generation existing today that came before us understands.
